{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64c7a229-a127-40e5-8059-b857a834bde0","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, the flags change:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/**/*[Category=Integration]\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` args from platform args. You'll need these NuGet packages in your test project:\n\n| Package | Enables |\n|---|---|\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` | `dotnet test` integration |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` | `--report-trx` |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` | `--coverage` |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` | `--crashdump` |\n| `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` | `--hangdump` |\n\n**Key differences from VSTest:**\n- `--filter` → `--treenode-filter` (with glob/property syntax `/**/*[Property=Value]`)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` / `--blame-hang-timeout` → `--hangdump` / `--hangdump-timeout`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4ca2b8d3-0082-4851-a066-5d6e554032de","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating a `dotnet test` command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences:\n- `--filter` → `--filter` (same, but can also use `--treenode-filter`)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (built-in)\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` (Microsoft.CodeCoverage collector is built-in)\n\n\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n- `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can still use `dotnet test` with the new arguments, or run the test executable directly. When `<UseTestingPlatform>true</UseTestingPlatform>` is set in the project file, `dotnet test` will use the new platform with its corresponding command-line options.\n\nOn .NET 8, the typical approach is to either run the test project directly with `dotnet run --project Tests.csproj -- <args>` or build and execute the test binary directly. The flag mappings for Microsoft.Testing.Platform include `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` for filtering tests.\n\nFor TRX reporting, I'd add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package and use `--report-trx`. Code coverage requires `Microsoft.CodeCoverage` with `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`. For crash and hang diagnostics, there are specific extensions and flags like `--crashdump` and `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m`.\n\nIf I want `dotnet test` to work with the new platform on .NET 8, I need to add `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` which bridges the compatibility gap. With that package, I can use `dotnet test` with the appropriate flags for filtering, reporting, and coverage...\n\nBuilding the command with all these options... I'm clarifying the command structure with the `--` separator that passes arguments to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, then listing out the required NuGet packages for each feature like trx reporting, code coverage, crash dumps, and hang dumps.","outputTokens":1520},"id":"8c3e55ab-a237-47ad-92d6-15c65d4183c7","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:17.016Z","parentId":"78f938cc-3639-4d0f-832c-bc4521418adf"}
